# Plan: Direction Support (LR, TD, BT, RL)

## Research Summary (from mermaid-ascii + beautiful-mermaid)

Both reference repos use the SAME Sugiyama layout for all directions. Key patterns:
1. LR: swap node width‚Üîheight BEFORE layout, then transpose positions (x‚Üîy) + swap back AFTER layout
2. BT: render as TD, then vertically flip the output canvas with character remapping
3. RL: render as LR, then horizontally flip the output canvas with character remapping

### Why swap dimensions for LR?
In TD mode, Sugiyama puts layers as rows (y) and positions within layers as columns (x).
Edge exits are bottom-center: (x + width/2, y + height - 1)
Edge entries are top-center: (x + width/2, y)

For LR, we want layers as columns and positions as rows:
- Swap width‚Üîheight BEFORE layout ‚Üí layout thinks nodes are tall-narrow
- Edge exit becomes (x + narrow_w/2, y + tall_h - 1) in layout coords
- After transposing (x‚Üîy) back: exit = (old_y + tall_h - 1, old_x + narrow_w/2) = right-center ‚úì
- Entry becomes left-center ‚úì

This avoids modifying the Sugiyama algorithm at all.

## Phases

### Phase 1: LR direction support (src/layout.rs + src/render.rs)
Worker 1 does layout.rs, Worker 2 does render.rs.

**Worker 1 ‚Äî layout.rs changes:**
- [x] Add `direction` parameter to `full_layout_with_padding` (pass from `gir.direction`)
- [x] When direction is LR or RL: swap width‚Üîheight in `node_dims` closure
- [x] When direction is LR or RL: swap H_GAP‚ÜîV_GAP in coordinate assignment
- [x] Everything else stays the same (Sugiyama, edge routing all unchanged)

**Worker 2 ‚Äî render.rs changes:**
- [x] Add `transpose_layout` function: swap x‚Üîy in LayoutNode positions and RoutedEdge waypoints, swap width‚Üîheight back to original
- [x] Add `flip_vertical` function for BT: reverse lines + remap chars (‚ñº‚Üî‚ñ≤, ‚îå‚Üî‚îî, ‚îê‚Üî‚îò, ‚î¨‚Üî‚î¥)
- [x] Add `flip_horizontal` function for RL: reverse each line + remap chars (‚ñ∫‚Üî‚óÑ, ‚îå‚Üî‚îê, ‚îî‚Üî‚îò, ‚îú‚Üî‚î§)
- [x] Modify `render()` to: transpose if LR/RL, render, then flip if BT/RL

### Phase 2: Wire direction through pipeline (src/lib.rs + src/main.rs)
- [x] `render_dsl` / `render_dsl_padded` already pass `gir` with direction ‚Äî just ensure layout receives it
- [x] `main.rs` already has --direction flag ‚Äî no changes needed
- [x] Test with: `echo -e "direction: LR\n[A] --> [B] --> [C]" | text-graph`

### Phase 3: Add LR/BT examples and verify
- [x] examples/lr_simple.txt ‚Äî `direction: LR\n[Start] --> [Middle] --> [End]`
- [x] examples/lr_fanout.txt ‚Äî `direction: LR\n[A] --> [B]\n[A] --> [C]\n[A] --> [D]`
- [x] examples/bt_simple.txt ‚Äî `direction: BT\n[A] --> [B] --> [C]`
- [x] `bash examples/gen.sh` ‚Äî all examples generate correctly
- [x] `cargo test` ‚Äî all tests pass

## Key Design Decision
The node box itself is ALWAYS drawn as a horizontal rectangle with text reading left-to-right.
Only the POSITION is transposed. Edge routing works automatically because exit/entry points are computed from (transposed) node dimensions.

